 characters and ideas as nowhere else. He takes the reader into the cramped confines of the colonial bar room, describing the friendships, misunderstandings and conflicts which were generated among the city's drinkers and investigates the profitability of running a tavern in a city which, until independence, set maximum prices on the cost of drinks and services in its public houses.Taverngoing, Thompson writes, fostered a sense of citizenship that influenced political debate in colonial Philadelphia and became an issue in the city's revolution. Opinionated and profoundly undeferential, taverngoers did more than drink; they forced their political leaders to consider whether and how public opinion could be represented in the counsels of a newly independent nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aPolitical culturezPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryx18th century. 0aPolitical culturezPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy18th century. 0aTaverns (Inns)zPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryx18th century. 0aTaverns (Inns)zPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy18th century. 4aAmerican History. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aBooks of Regional Interest. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn eBook Package Archive 1898-1999 (pre Pub)z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220428540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812204285423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812204285.jpg  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041349-6  Penn Press eBook Package American Histor